            "creation_date": 1501403745,
            "body": "<p>Ah, I remember the similar question from yesterday.  C-:=<\/p>\n\n<p>So, as I said yesterday, it is almost always a bad practice to declare a function that accepts parameters of type <code>Object<\/code>. Functions that accept <code>Object<\/code> parameters are only found in framework-level or system-level programming.  And when doing framework-level or system-level programming, you have no notion of application-level entities, so you don't know of any <code>Car<\/code>, <code>Computer<\/code> or <code>Mobile<\/code>, so there is no possibility to use <code>instanceof<\/code> like this.<\/p>\n\n<p>Generally, any use of <code>instanceof<\/code> is a sign of something being done wrongly.  The industry term for this is \"code smell\".  <\/p>\n\n<p>There are extremely few and very specific cases where passing an <code>Object<\/code> argument and using <code>instanceof<\/code> is necessary and appropriate, as for example when coding a <code>boolean equals( Object other )<\/code> method.  Whenever you see <code>Object<\/code> arguments and <code>instanceof<\/code> outside of these very few well known cases, it is a code smell.  Don't do it.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would insist that in order for your code not to smell, you would need to come up with a common base class.  Yesterday's example involved <code>Car<\/code>, <code>Motorcycle<\/code> and <code>Bicycle<\/code>, and I suggested coming up with a <code>Vehicle<\/code> base class.  Now you have chosen the classes to be <code>Car<\/code>, <code>Computer<\/code>, and <code>Mobile<\/code> in an effort to indicate that they share no common functionality.  I would suggest that:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Either these classes really share no common functionality, in which case passing them as <code>Object<\/code> and using <code>instanceof<\/code> is bad practice, certainly to be viewed as code smell and not pass any code review in the industry, or<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>There is still some way to extract a common base class (or interface) which can declare a <code>validate()<\/code> method so as to avoid passing <code>Object<\/code> arguments and using <code>instanceof<\/code>. It could be <code>Gadget<\/code>, or <code>MyWorldEntity<\/code>, or <code>Validatable<\/code>.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n",
            "answer_id": 45397923,
            "question_id": 45397813
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/iypYQ.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 6358010,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4934560,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4934560/b%c3%a1lint",
                "reputation": 4069,
                "display_name": "B&#225;lint",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1501403704,
            "creation_date": 1501403704,
            "body": "<p>There should be absolutely no reason to deal with three completely different objects in the same method. You should define an interface (for example <code>Validateable<\/code>) and put a validate method in it:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>interface Validateable {\n    public void validate();\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then make the classes implement it<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Car implements Validateable { ... }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45397919,
            "question_id": 45397813
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/oYplt.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 8263873,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6214222,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6214222/keiwan",
                "reputation": 8321,
                "display_name": "Keiwan",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1501403997,
            "creation_date": 1501403997,
            "body": "<p>You have multiple options. One would be to let the objects do the validation themselves using an interface that requires a <code>validate()<\/code> method as pointed out in the comments by @dunni.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you definitely need your validation to be performed outside of the individual classes without changing any of their implementation you could use method overloading. Create multiple functions called <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>private void validateParams(Type obj)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>with the respective type of the object to validate and implement the specific validation for that type in there. So you'd have methods like:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>private void validateParams(Computer computer) {...}\nprivate void validateParams(Car car) {...}\nprivate void validateParams(Mobile mobile) {...}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and you can call all of them using:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>validateParams(obj) // where obj is of type Computer, Car or Mobile\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45397955,
            "question_id": 45397813
        }
    ],
